He believed in the natural rights of people, and that they're all connected - if one is taken away, the others lose value too.  He thought the government should stay out of it and not mess with those rights.  He had this weird idea that in the "state of nature," the strong and mean people were the ones who got ahead, but that's not how it should be in a civilized society.

To create this perfect society, Taylor thought the government should be all about acknowledging the good and bad in people.  He was super strict about his ideas on right and wrong, and he said that because government is run by people, it's gotta be human too.  He said that good principles are about protecting private property, helping out farmers, and keeping capitalism in check, and that a government based on those principles would work just fine no matter who's in charge.  But, he thought self-interest was a major problem, and that it's only bad when it's used to hurt others.

Taylor was all about keeping the government small and limited, just like the Constitution says.  He didn't want the feds to have any more power than they absolutely needed, 'cause he knew that would just make 'em expensive and, like, super controlling.  But at the same time, he thought that just following the Constitution literally without thinking about what the people who wrote it meant could be a bad idea.  He also thought the Declaration of Independence was way more important than the Constitution, 'cause it talks about the US being a bunch of separate states rather than just one big nation.

Looking back at Figure 17, we noticed that there was a huge drop in commuter log submissions during the third month of the project. That was pretty disappointing, and it's hard to figure out why that happened. You'd think that with winter coming to a New England campus, people would be less likely to commute by bike or on foot, which could explain part of the drop. Also, December's a crazy time with everyone wrapping up schoolwork and grades, which might make people forget all about filling out that commuter log. On top of that, December's the start of the holiday season, and everyone's busy getting ready for a long break from campus. When classes start up again in late January, it makes sense that log submissions would be low that month too. But none of that really explains why submissions were so low in February. Maybe projects like this one just naturally lose steam after the initial excitement wears off. So, we came up with the Carpool Challenge Week in March to try and get people excited again, and it worked - we saw an increase in log submissions that month. One of the biggest challenges we faced was keeping the project going when people naturally lose interest, and dealing with the holiday and semester breaks that are a part of higher education. 

Another problem we encountered with this project (and probably any similar one) is that people love the freedom and independence that comes with driving their cars. That's just part of our culture, so we needed to offer incentives to get people to switch to alternative modes of transportation. We gave out a bunch of gift cards to local places, but it would've been cool to see how bigger prizes like a bike, a hybrid car, or an electric car might've boosted participation. That could've helped us avoid that dip in engagement we saw. We kept the same prizes throughout the project, which might not have been the best idea. If we'd announced bigger and better prizes as the project went on - like adding a bike in December and a car in January - I bet people would've been way more into it.

So, you're probably wondering what an ETF is. Well, it's like a hybrid between an index fund and a stock – it tracks an index, commodity, or a bunch of assets, but trades like a single stock on the exchange. It gives you the benefits of owning a bunch of different things (like an index fund) and the flexibility to sell short, buy on margin, and even buy just one share, just like with a stock. And the best part? The fees for ETFs are way lower than those of the average mutual fund. However, there are some downsides – you gotta pay a commission for each trade, just like with stocks. Plus, there are a ton of different ETFs to choose from, which is awesome, but also kinda overwhelming. When picking an ETF, it's smart to really think about whether the benefits, like diversification, are actually working for you, and to what extent.

We're gonna take a closer look at the ETF IHF and its top 10 holdings, which account for about 63.6% of its assets. It'd be a real pain to go over all the holdings, so we're just gonna focus on the top 10. Here are the top 10 holdings and their share of the ETF's assets.

To figure out how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF as a whole, we're gonna use their current percentages to calculate their contribution to a portfolio's Beta and Return, like if the portfolio was made up of just these 10 stocks in the same proportions as the ETF. We got the Beta and Return calculations below.

From the chart, it's pretty clear that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings would have a higher return (6.11% higher) and lower Beta (0.12 lower) than the ETF. But here's the thing – it's possible that these two portfolios aren't actually that different from each other.

To check if they are actually different, we're gonna calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and compare it to the ETF's standard deviation.

I was reading about Edgar Allan Poe's poem "Dream-Land" and I'm convinced it's one of his best works. In the poem, Poe mentions the term "Thulé" twice, which is a term that he apparently picked up from Virgil. Virgil used it to describe an island off the northern coast of Britain that the ancient Greeks thought was the edge of the known world, but people think Poe got it from someone else too. Poe was really into German writers like Goethe, and it shows. 

This connection is a big deal because it proves how well-read Poe was. Karl J. Arndt, a writer who studied Poe and Goethe, noticed that their poems were similar and even thought Poe was copying Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature has a whole section on Goethe, who was famous for writing the poetic drama Faust, which was published in two parts in 1808 and 1832. There's a poem within Faust called "The King of Thule" that's pretty dark and talks about a king who loses his wife and then drowns his sorrows in booze. The king's story is kind of like the main character in "Dream-Land", maybe even a dark mirror image of Poe's own struggles with drinking. Goethe's Faust was even turned into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, just a year before Poe used the term Thule in another poem.

Poe mentioned Thule twice in his writings, first in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and then again in "Dream-Land" as the start and end of the poem. It's like "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" are two poems that go together. In "Dream-Land", the speaker describes a place called Thule that's dark, lonely, and haunted by dead friends. It's like he's stepping into Goethe's world. Goethe was a big deal in Poe's time, and Poe even admired Alfred Tennyson, who was friends with Goethe. Poe probably knew about Goethe's work through all the reproductions of his work that were happening after it was first published.

If a customer was injured after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store under California law, could they get punitive damages if the store manager, Paul Martin, was acting with malice because he was told twice about the spill but didn't clean it up for half an hour because he was eating dinner?  I don't think a judge would just dismiss the customer's claim for punitive damages without a fight. To get punitive damages, the customer, Jennifer Palmer, would need to show that the store manager acted on purpose with a bad intention to cause harm, or that he acted really badly and didn't care about the consequences. Palmer will be able to argue that Martin should have known that not cleaning the spill would be a problem because there were already a bunch of people slipping and falling in the store before her accident, and he still didn't do anything about it. Palmer might have a point, but it's not super strong because there were only six slip-and-fall incidents that year and Martin still didn't do enough to keep the store safe.

It looks like Martin was pretty clueless because on October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee, Rich Wayne, told him about the applesauce spill, and Martin basically said he was too busy eating dinner to deal with customer complaints. Then, at 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also told him about the spill, and he said the same thing. It wasn't until 30 minutes later, at 5:30 pm, that Palmer slipped and fell on the spill and hurt her back. Before Palmer's accident, there had already been five slip-and-fall incidents in 2009 at the store. Palmer is now suing D&D for both compensatory and punitive damages, and we're wondering if we should file a motion to get rid of the punitive damage claim.

In California, if someone gets hurt because the other person didn't do what they were supposed to do (like keep the store safe), they can get punitive damages if the other person acted really badly and didn't care about the consequences. The law says that's malice if the person knew what they were doing was going to hurt someone, or if they were really reckless and didn't care about the consequences. It's like when someone knows that what they're doing is going to hurt someone, but they do it anyway. That's not cool.

It's been almost four years since I took an Islam course at CBC, where discussions often revolved around whether Islam is a hostile religion.  In my opinion, this question is more relevant now than ever.  Observing the mass media's shift from a hostile view of Islam to over-the-top tolerance since 9/11 has been pretty mind-blowing.  Back in 2001, it was unthinkable to have a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, who has family ties to Islam, running for office.

The story of the Prophet's life really fascinates me.  I've learned that it's almost like a biography of a hero, but it contradicts what I thought I knew about Muhammad.  According to history, I thought Muhammad forced people to convert to Islam by conquering tribes and imposing his faith on them, but the biography portrays him as a humble martyr who was misunderstood and even humbled himself to others.  People were drawn to his teachings because of some kind of inner light or something, not because they were coerced.

It's also weird how the stories of Muhammad's life have some parallels to the story of Jesus – like the time he fed a bunch of people with a small amount of food and had some left over.  I get the feeling that the writers wanted to make Muhammad out to be this super humble guy who didn't need to prove anything, but just lived life with integrity and performed miracles because that's who he was.  It's like they're watering down the real miracle of Jesus and trying to ride his coattails.

I've also noticed that the biography includes a lot of stories that seem to be about providing proof that people converted to Islam on their own free will.  But the problem is that these stories are often based on second-hand accounts and seem suspicious because of that.  It's like they're trying to build a case for the validity of the stories, but it actually makes them seem less believable.

What really gets me is that they're trying to paint Muhammad as this super nice and wise guy who's above reproach.  But history says that's not true, and I wonder if Muslims today even know the real story about Muhammad's rise to power.

It's like the original message of Jesus got lost in the shuffle as Christianity evolved after he was gone.  If we look at the big picture, it seems like Christianity has been moving further and further away from its roots.  I think we're starting to see a shift, though.  There are more people who care about the real story of Jesus and the ideas he stood for.  While some folks might stick with tradition, I think they'll be outnumbered.  Christians are becoming more aware of their history, and this awareness is going to keep growing.  It's like a longing will start to build up, to figure out what's real and what's been added to the story over the years.  It might take a long time - decades or even centuries - but eventually, Christianity will swing back to its original form.  A movement will emerge, and it will start stripping away all the extra stuff that's built up over time.  It's like the clock will start ticking backwards.  When this happens, people in the US and Europe will start to focus on what Jesus really taught, and the church will be there to guide them.  But here's the thing - because we're going back to basics, we'll see a lot less variety in what people believe.  Instead of all the different branches of Christianity, we'll see a lot more things in common.  History is full of examples of this kind of reversal.  Think about how the Roman Empire used to persecute Christians, but later became Christian itself.  Or how our country went from having African-American slaves to having African-American leaders.  A similar reversal is coming for Christianity, and it will be a journey back to the source.  To make this happen, people need to start seeing Jesus' words as metaphors, not literal rules.  So, what happened to the original message of Jesus after he was gone?

Looking back, it's pretty obvious that Jesus was a part of the Jewish tradition.  When the Romans took over Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., the Jewish people didn't all agree on the same thing.  They split into different groups - the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and just regular people.  Monotheism, the idea of a divinely revealed religion, and the importance of the Hebrew scriptures were all key parts of Judaism at that time.  It's interesting to think about how different the Jewish people were, and how that laid the groundwork for Christianity.

I think The Jungle shows how people's true nature is deep down selfish and self-centered. All they care about is making their lives as good as possible and not really considering anyone else. The Jungle proves this in lots of ways. It's super obvious with the owners and managers of the huge factories. All they want to do is make their companies as huge and awesome as possible, no matter who gets hurt or what gets in their way. They just don't care about anything else. Upton Sinclair's writing paints a picture of the super bad stuff they're causing by making pollution, like all the smoke and gross stuff coming from the factories. He shows that the owners don't care about anyone or anything that gets hurt. They don't even care about the people working for them or the animals living near the factories. They're all about making money and don't care who they have to step on to get it.

The owners and managers were also super bad to their employees, making them work crazy hours and then just laying them off without warning or helping them find a new job. Back when The Jungle was set, there weren't any laws to protect workers, so the owners and managers could do whatever they wanted. The people working in Packingtown were basically expected to deal with the awful conditions all the time, both at work and at home. There were some unions trying to help, but they were more about making money off the workers than actually helping them. The workers were treated so badly and had no way out of the system that they were basically slaves, and Sinclair said that's just as bad as the old slave system.

Many authors use different techniques to influence their readers' feelings about important topics, and some are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald is a master of using these techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, he pairs words that don't normally go together to create a certain atmosphere around a subject. Other times, he adds meaning to a symbol, then uses it for the same purpose. Fitzgerald uses the latter technique with lots of colors, like gold, green, red, and pink. In The Great Gatsby, he builds up meaning for colors, specifically white and gray, then uses that meaning to give readers a certain feeling about an important thing.

Fitzgerald's use of white and gray is really interesting. He gives them a meaning of uniformity, with white being fancy and high class, and gray being old and faded. He sets up this meaning right at the beginning of the novel by using them a lot. People like Daisy and Jordan are always dressed in white - almost everyone is, actually. Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby's party, Tom wears a white shirt when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine looks like she's been powdered into a milky white complexion. The only time people aren't wearing white is when Nick is describing Gatsby's party, and the halls are a gaudy mess of bright colors. Fitzgerald takes it further by using these colors on everyday, unimportant things, like when Nick goes to work, he goes down the white canyons of lower New York, and when he makes his schedule, the names of people at Gatsby's parties are just gray names.

He even uses these colors to describe plain or regular people and places: Jordan and Daisy had a white girlhood together, there are gray cars and gray land in the valley of ashes, the kid on the train is gray, and the dog seller is an old gray guy. After Fitzgerald establishes the meaning of white and gray, he uses them to show that certain subjects are unimportant or uniform. He starts this with Daisy, after a long time without using these colors, he describes her as wearing white in a little white roadster, and suddenly she seems less like a person and more like just something that Gatsby wants and longs for. He uses more of this technique with Daisy to give her the impression of being a more uniform addition, like when there's a gray haze around her fur collar, or when she's wearing a white dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

I recently looked into San Diego County's agricultural scene, and it's totally thriving thanks to its awesome climate. The county is producing a ton of awesome stuff, like juicy tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and spicy peppers. It's super popular for organic community supported agriculture food, with a bunch of local organizations having long waiting lists for their products, especially organic eggs and milk. Many of these farms also offer tours and activities like hiking and birdwatching, which is a win-win for landowners who can benefit from government programs and still get to enjoy the outdoors. It's like getting paid to be a nature lover!

The cool thing about organic farming is that it lets you have a super diverse ecosystem with tons of wildlife and plants, since you don't use any harsh chemicals. However, it can be a bit more labor-intensive and costly than conventional farming. You need to work harder to keep pests and weeds under control and fertilize the soil naturally, and sometimes you end up losing more crops than you would with traditional methods. Plus, a small organic farm can't compete with the efficiency of a big operation. But, there are some other practices that can help the environment and wildlife, like planting cover crops and strategic grazing rotation, which can be more expensive. That's why it might be helpful for landowners to get some financial assistance or expert advice on how to maximize profits and habitat quality.

The land I chose for this scenario is a 160-acre plot in Potrero, an area in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It's a mix of chaparral, non-native grassland, and oak woodland right next to the Cleveland National Forest. It's located in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion, which is part of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but it covers over a hundred species of plants and animals, some of which are endangered, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the California gnatcatcher, and others that might be listed soon, like the burrowing owls. This land has a rich history, having been inhabited by Native Americans for centuries and later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s.

I picked this piece of land from a real estate website and looked into government programs to see what a small farmer might be able to do to cut costs and preserve wildlife-friendly operations. I found an organic farm in the same area that I used as a model for this scenario.

When it comes to negotiation, culture plays a really big role. Culture isn't just one thing; it's also about what it's not and what it means. It's not a single, uniform thing, and it's definitely not the same for everyone. Think about saying things like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" - these are way too broad and don't make any sense. It's actually more helpful to understand what culture means in the context of a specific situation and how it'll affect the negotiation. When you're dealing with a different culture, you naturally compare it to your own, and that's when things get interesting.

Trying to get to know a different culture or mindset can be like studying its history or realizing its biases. Instead of judging or trying to change it, you just have to accept it as it is and work within its boundaries, especially when you're negotiating and you're in a weaker position. If you're in a foreign territory, respecting their traditions and beliefs can help you get past any cultural obstacles and move the negotiation forward.

Now, here's the thing: culture isn't just about countries or nationalities. Companies have their own culture too, and it can be totally different from one company to another. For instance, some companies are super strict about work hours, while others are super relaxed. You can see this in how they dress, how they communicate, and even who they hire. Some companies really encourage employees to be philanthropic, while others only let them do it through certain approved charities. Looking at how American companies differ from each other (and even within the same company, depending on the region or urban vs. suburban) shows just how diverse culture can be.

Understanding values is even more important, because they explain why a culture is the way it is. If saving face or community harmony is a big deal, you won't publicly shame your company or boss to get ahead in negotiations. On the other hand, if a culture values getting the best deal possible, they won't settle for anything less. Knowing these generalities can help you prepare for negotiations, but it's also helpful to get to know your opponent on a personal level to make the negotiation more effective.

There's this crazy quote from Psalm 14 in the Christian Bible, "The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’" It gets referenced by St. Anselm in his argument about God's existence, and our other dude, Thomas Aquinas, seems to agree with him. Since we're gonna be talking about their arguments, we'll just assume they're both on the same page about the existence of God, specifically the God from the Bible. If we're talking about some random God-type, it wouldn't be a fair comparison, so let's just roll with it. 

That said, I think both of these guys make some good points, but neither really lays out a solid, all-around case for believing in God. To understand this, let's break down Anselm's argument first. Anselm's all about finding proof of God within yourself, kinda like how you can know something's true just by thinking about it. He says that because God exists in our minds, we can't even imagine a world without him. It's a pretty weird concept, but basically, he's saying that you don't need any outside evidence to believe in God – just your own thoughts. He's talking about faith, you know, when you believe in something even if there's no concrete proof. 

Now, Aquinas is all about using logic and facts to prove God's existence, no faith required. This would be super helpful for getting new people into Christianity, since you wouldn't have to convince them to believe in something they can't see. Aquinas breaks down five different ways to prove God's existence: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. He's all about how using logic can show you that God has to exist. Think of it like trying to finish a puzzle – if you know all the other pieces, you can figure out what the missing one looks like even if you can't see it.

Somewhere around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who'd later be known as Buddha was born. He'd eventually give up the world and get enlightened, and his teachings became the foundation for Buddhism—the orthodox branch of which is Theravada Buddhism. The religion is over two thousand five hundred years old, and it looks really different from what it was like when Buddha was alive. You can see this in places like Sri Lanka, a Theravada nation, where they celebrate the annual water-cutting ceremony. Monks and regular people both participate, and it's got some spiritual significance, even though Buddha never taught about anything like that. These differences run all the way from surface-level traditions to the core ideas that make up the religion. Over time, the Theravada Buddhist community has changed its core principles from both the monk's perspective and the regular person's. This happened due to both external and internal forces, some good and some bad.

In this discussion, we'll use some terms a lot. When we say 'internal force,' we mean something that comes from within the Buddhist community, regardless of whether someone's a monk or not. An 'external force' is any influence from outside the Buddhist world. A 'hostile force' is something that harms or tries to harm the Buddhist community, usually because of a negative view of Buddhism. A 'benign force' is any influence that doesn't want to hurt or help Buddhism, but might end up doing one or the other anyway. These terms will come up a lot as we talk about this.

First off, it's essential to understand the basics of the religion—the core ideas that make up Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists look to the three jewels: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha for guidance. The Dhamma is basically made up of the Tripitaka—the three baskets of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka has all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka has the rules for monks and regular people, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka has the deeper, more philosophical ideas of Buddhism. Concepts like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (the idea that life is suffering), and Anicca (how everything's temporary) are all part of this. Recognizing these ideas can help you escape Sansara—the cycle of death and rebirth, which keeps going on and on. Along with Sansara, when you become enlightened, you'll also break free from lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). In the Vinaya Pitaka, there are rules laid out for how to live your life. For regular people, there are five basic rules (don't kill, don't lie, don't steal, don't misbehave, and don't take drugs). For monks, there are many more rules to follow. The core idea of Buddhism is the four noble truths: first, that life is suffering (Dukkha); second, that attachment causes suffering; and third, that suffering can be overcome.

The US and Mexico had this crazy long-standing feud that lasted for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  It was like, the ultimate rivalry, and it really came to a head during the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848. The US basically attacked Mexico, took over Texas and the Southwest, and it was a pretty intense clash.  Before the First World War, they were still having all these issues, but it finally started to die down.  This whole thing started because Americans and Mexicans had totally different ideas about stuff like religion, culture, and traditions, and they also had major disagreements over material things (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
It's not just the US and Mexico - lots of countries that share borders tend to have these kinds of rivalries.  The US and Mexico are actually kind of like many other countries that have been stuck in these long-term rivalries with their neighbors.  David M. Pletcher (1977) said something pretty interesting, "Only in Mexico and Cuba can you find long-lasting American diplomatic problems" (p. 41).  These countries are basically right next to the US, and they've been at odds with the US for a while now.  Other countries in Latin America, on the other hand, have gotten along pretty well with the US.

One of the big issues was that the US and Mexico had totally different ideas about religion - and this has been a major problem in lots of countries throughout history.  Sally Frahm (2001) pointed out that Americans used to be super opposed to Catholicism and monarchy in the 18th and 19th centuries (p.86).  It's kind of like how the Cold War was this huge ideological struggle between the US and the Soviet Union, except in this case, it wasn't about politics, but about whether they were Protestant or Catholic.  This whole thing started because the English and Spanish had a bunch of distrust, and the US and Mexico just inherited that.  This made it really hard for them to get along.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) counted up 17 different disputes between the US and Mexico during this 57-year rivalry period.  Most of these disputes were about territory and border problems, like bandits and outlaws crossing the border.  The US and Mexico finally started to calm down when Mexico became super dependent on the US, and then they both started to focus more on economic stuff rather than expanding territory (Schmitt 1974 p. 109-110).

Fifteen years ago, my life took a drastic turn due to a health condition that I never expected to affect me. I was a nurse at the time, and I had chosen that career path to guarantee a sense of security that I never had as a child. The constant advice I received as a kid, "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick," made me think that nursing was a safe bet. So, I put aside my dreams of being a scientist or journalist – a mix of both would've been awesome – and became a nurse.

Now, here I am, 46 years old, single, and living on Social Security Disability after fifteen years. I've got nothing left to call my own, and every day is a struggle to stay afloat. My life feels like an ongoing battle for security, safety, and self-respect. Yet, amidst this chaos, I've learned one thing for sure: without the help of my family and a few genuine friends, I wouldn't have made it through these years. And trust me, when disaster strikes, you won't feel as strong as you thought you'd be.

My point is, emergencies will come in all shapes and sizes – and there's no way to prepare for everything. No matter how much you prepare, some situations are just too big to handle on your own.

I agree that we should stop putting all our eggs in the US government's basket, as it's crumbling anyway. However, I'd rather see Americans learn to trust and help each other, rather than building individual fallout shelters. The idea of rugged individualism that the Conservatives talk about is a myth; it was actually our ancestors' compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources that kept them going through tough times. Those pioneers who crossed the Rockies didn't make it to the coast alone – they relied on their community.

So, by all means, prepare. I'm prepared – I've got a disaster kit, first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, and all the essentials. But it's not just about being prepared; it's also about building connections with your neighbors. Get to know the people around you, and work together to make your community stronger. If you've got the land and resources for a small farm, canning or preserving your own food is a fantastic idea, as is a wood stove – just make sure you don't live in an apartment.

So, why do living things evolve the way they do? Is there some hidden force guiding the direction of change? Even back in 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said zoologists were just starting to imagine describing organic forms in math terms, but we're not much further along today. Recently, math has been applied to the way shell-building creatures, like snails, grow and change over time (like their great-great-grandparents). Our study is exploring how math can help us figure out what makes the shapes of snail shells change. We took X-rays of snail species to measure the patterns that make up their shells, then plugged those numbers into this super cool computer program called CerioShell. We used those results to imagine what snail shells might look like if they'd evolved differently. We're combining that with some hands-on experiments to understand how shell shapes change over millions of years.

Imagine a snail shell as a spiral tube that grows and grows over time - it's like a big, twisty road that winds its way through space. Each twist is called a whorl, and they all spiral around a central axis (like a big, invisible pole) that runs through the shell's middle. The speed at which the whorls get bigger can vary, and there's a clear line between each twist, called a suture. In most shells, the biggest twist is the last one (the body whorl), and the rest are called the spire. The top point of the spire is the apex, and the bottom is the base. The snail sticks out of its shell through a hole called the aperture.

You can look at shells from different angles - from the top, from the bottom, from the front, or from the back. Usually, people look at shells with the aperture facing them and the apex pointing up.

Here's a way to count the twists: first, look at the shell from the top, then find where the first twist starts. Draw a line that splits the shell in two, and then count the twists from there - you can even estimate a quarter of a twist if you're not sure. A shell can be thought of as a series of holes that move through time and space as the snail builds its shell. By tracking the path of the hole, you can use math to understand how the shell grows. This lets you play around with different shell-building rules and see how they would affect the snail's shell shape.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has been pretty much the same for the past ten years.  It's weird because the country is doing okay on other things like getting clean water and sanitation, but it's really struggling to meet its targets for child and maternal health by 2015.  I'm gonna get into the reasons for this below, and they show that the country needs to improve its whole health system instead of just focusing on individual programs.

It's cool that Indonesia has gotten better at having skilled health workers at births, with 72% of births now meeting this target.  But what's strange is that this number includes traditional workers like midwives who can't do much if things get complicated.  So, the improvements in this area aren't as great as they seem, and there's still lots to be done.  The number of kids under five who get treated for diarrhea by a health pro has actually gone down, and the data on postnatal care is sketchy, but it's clear that this is a problem too.  We're talking low rates all over the country.

C-section rates are way too low at about 4%, and that's not the only thing that's concerning.  The rates are way higher in cities (like 7%) than in rural areas (only 2%).  This shows that healthcare services are basically only available in cities.  Another problem is that some people can't access healthcare services because they can't afford it.  There's a huge gap in service use between the poorest and richest people in the country.

Now we're talking about what to do next to improve neonatal and maternal care.  The big question is how to actually get more people access to healthcare services.  Should Indonesia focus on specific programs or strengthen its whole healthcare system instead of just focusing on pre and post-pregnancy care for moms and babies?  I think program-specific approaches are tempting because they have clear goals and can produce quick results.  But there are some downsides.  One problem is that when we focus too much on one area, other areas don't get enough funding or resources.  Another problem is that all these separate programs can create a lot of extra work and duplication of services.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulously detailed descriptions and focus on the lives of the upper class during that era.  Two notable exceptions, however, are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights.  These novels stray from the typical tradition by incorporating elements of mystery and a touch of the bizarre, which helps to bring the characters to life and reveal their inner thoughts and emotions in a more profound way. 

One of the most memorable scenes from an Oliver Twist passage reads: "And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly." 

These novels often use mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, but the specifics vary in each case. In Oliver Twist, these strange events often provide insight into Oliver's inner turmoil, what torments him, and his growing awareness of the harsh realities surrounding him. When Oliver relives the shooting in chapter 28, it's like he's reliving it in a dream, as he desperately searches for help. This passage highlights Oliver's lack of control over the events unfolding around him, as well as his dire situation, which is evident in his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting overwhelms him, numbing all his senses as he fails to notice the "unseen hand" carrying him away; he's re-experiencing his despair without the initial shock of pain, now linked with ongoing fear. This scene raises questions about whose fault Oliver's misfortune is, as it's clear it wasn't his own. This reinforces the idea that Oliver has little control over his life, unable to even attempt to change the outcome, even when his life is at risk. This scene also implies a growing sense of defeat in Oliver, as if Fagin has broken him, making him accept his despair and lose his ability to react. 

In another passage from Wuthering Heights, we find: "The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours."

It's been a couple years since I worked with a bunch of Elementary aged students in an after school program, teaching them whatever subject they were struggling with. My strengths were in English and reading, but I did my best to help them out in other areas too. I was asked to work one-on-one with this kid named Adrian - I think he was in either third or fourth grade - who was really struggling to read. It was weird, though; I realized that this kid was having some pretty strange problems. Some letters he could read perfectly, while others were completely off. I figured it had to be something other than what I thought at first, since he spoke perfect English, but I'm pretty sure he's Latino. I worked with him for a while, trying to figure out what was going on, but it wasn't until I met his mom that things became clear. She walked in on us while we were hanging out (I was basically babysitting him while the rest of the group was on a field trip), and it turned out she only spoke Spanish. Using my limited Spanish skills, we were able to communicate a little bit, and it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian could read, but he just didn't know the English alphabet that well. I don't know if that little epiphany helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I tell this story to point out how language barriers can be a big problem in schools, especially here in California. I also want to show that it's not always as obvious as we think it is, even for kids who speak perfect English. Reading can be a huge obstacle for them. Everyone can agree on that, so what's the solution? For Adrian, it was pretty simple: tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciations. But for the kids who barely speak English, it's way more complicated. There isn't just one answer. We've got dual language systems, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes - none of those things are going to fix this problem on their own.  The key is to combine them all.

First off, I think the dual language system is a great idea. Not just for kids who speak Spanish as their first language, but for all of them. Apparently, kids in two-way bilingual education programs outperform their peers academically. A lot of people are scared of this idea, thinking it's a waste of resources and that most kids won't benefit from it. But that's not true. If we made these programs the norm, rather than the exception, all kids would be helped by it. So, how do we make this happen? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? That wouldn't be realistic or fair. But I think it's a good idea to have bilingual tutors, aids, or whatever you want to call them. That way, we can make these programs work.

We've all been told from a young age that there's something out there that's beyond our understanding. Some of us go to church, while others go to temple or try to figure things out on our own. Many of us just stick with what our parents taught us, but others reject it all and think there's just nothing more to life than what we can see and touch. We might adopt one set of values, then change our minds and switch to another. Whatever we choose, we're trying to figure out who we are through our own way of looking at the world. We're searching for a light in the dark to guide us out of the shadows and into the light.

My dad and I sat on the porch, listening to the rain pound against the tin roof while we both smoked. He said his favorite kind of bird was the cardinal, and just kept staring off into the rain. He looked really thin, and his clothes hung loose on him. I knew he was struggling. I felt scared and alone, and I didn't want to talk about how much I was going to miss him because it would make it too real for both of us. So I just hugged him, sat back down, and joined him in staring out into the rain.

My dad passed away in December, just a few days after my 22nd birthday. The chemo and radiation had kept him alive when the doctors thought it was time to let go, but it was just prolonging the pain. I didn't know what kind of God would do that. I didn't pray that night, and if there was a God, I thought he had stopped listening to me a long time ago.

I didn't want to watch him die, so I didn't. I wanted to remember my dad for how he lived, not how he died. I knew him better than anyone else, and I knew he wouldn't have wanted me to watch him go. So I just curled up in a ball and waited for the news. But nobody even called me.

The term "Gothic Novel" seems like an oxymoron, as Ian Watt described it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel - a mix of "old" and "new." This genre has been both praised and criticized for its superficiality and its ability to evoke a sense of the "terrible sublime" (Burke). The original "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, combined elements from both "ancient" and "modern" romances to create the prototype for the Gothic genre. By blending old theatrical clichés with new, naturalistic writing styles, Walpole created what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). Gothic literature often incorporates nods to medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. At the time of The Castle of Otranto's release, the term "gothic" was already associated with various peoples, styles, and time periods, implying it was outdated and unsophisticated compared to modern societal and literary advancements. The combination of the theatrical, old-fashioned "Gothic" and the novel's new format, which provided readers with a more personal glimpse into character psychology, helped the Gothic genre endure and remain relevant, becoming both outdated and new to readers who came across it long after its initial writing.

One of the key ideas present in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval notion of chivalry, which involves training a proper knight, is reinterpreted in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry was essential to Gothic writers like Walpole because it represented the ideal knight - brave, honorable, and competent - and contrasted it with the perceived lack of these ideals in their own society. By romanticizing and idealizing the chivalric past, Gothic writers attempted to improve the present. Given the tumultuous political climate when Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto, and the unfair accusations he faced, it's possible that he believed the morality and goodness of the Gothic era had been lost in modern society. This idea is evident in characters like Frederic, who embodies many chivalric traits, such as his royal status, his history of suffering, and his supposed bravery in the face of tragedy. The description of Frederic is riddled with traditional chivalric images, making him an exaggerated representation of the "gallant and courteous Knight" trope, which would later become a hallmark of Gothic literature (Walpole 66).

The flow of goods from the point when a customer places an order all the way back to the raw materials stage is referred to as supply chain management. Keith Oliver, a consultant, coined the term in 1982. He described the process of planning, implementing, and controlling the entire supply chain in order to meet customers' needs quickly and efficiently. The six key components of a supply chain are production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers utilize these six components to deliver top-notch customer service.

The first step in the supply chain process is production. It serves as the foundation for the entire chain. The production stage outlines the when, why, where, and how of production. To do this, managers need to figure out what customers want. One way to do that is by analyzing the market, which is the biggest indicator of customer demand. Once managers have a handle on customer demand, they can decide what products to produce and how many to make. They also need to decide where the products will be produced and which plant will be the best fit for volume and quality, all while keeping the customer's needs in mind. After that, managers focus on scheduling workloads and equipment maintenance. Every detail is crucial in the production process. If not planned carefully, it can end up costing the company a lot of time and money in the long run.

For instance, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target retail stores. Both companies have a blueprint for every aspect of the business, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments from trucks. Having a clear plan helps the company run smoothly and prevents confusion.

The second essential element in supply chain management is supply. It involves making strategic decisions about a facility's core capabilities and outsourcing partnerships. A company might have multiple divisions for producing a single product, each with its own equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager needs to decide which division is best suited for the different processes of the product. They might also choose to outsource work to other companies to achieve velocity, which is the ability to provide high-quality products with flexibility while keeping costs low.

There's this wild sign on the street that says, "Hitler is alive in Burma". It's like something right out of a crazy dream. Ellen Page from Juno is standing on a corner, holding a cardboard sign with this unsettling message written in Sharpie. Burma, or Myanmar, is this Southeast Asian country that's been ruled by a super oppressive government since 1962. They overthrew the government in a military coup, and things escalated quickly from there. In 2007, monks led some massive protests called the "Saffron Revolution" because of their bright orange robes. It was huge, with people from all over starting to take notice. At first, the government let them march, but then things got super violent - the military even broke into monasteries and attacked people. Journalists got arrested just for showing up, and a Japanese photographer named Kenji Nagai got killed for being in the middle of it all. The official death count is like, 13, but a high-ranking officer who defected from the army said there were thousands more. 

This isn't new, man. Governments wanting to keep control over people has been going on forever. Ancient Roman emperors thought they were gods, Japanese emperors are basically considered divine, and our current prez, George W. Bush, has some weird connections to this Ted Haggard guy who's like the leader of some crazy group. There are so many examples of this - like that time in 1989 when people protested in Tiananmen Square and the Chinese government claimed only a few hundred died, but other sources say it was way more like 2,000-3,000. Then there was the Rwandan genocide where Hutu militias killed all these people, and of course, there was the whole "Third Reich" thing where Hitler and his crew went around killing Jews and others. It's all just super messed up.

Duke Ellington's impact on jazz is largely due to his impressive lifespan, which allowed him to continually shape his orchestra and create new music. Although he's often not prominent on the piano in his compositions, Ellington's skill as a composer shines through in the rich and complex pieces he created that showed off each band member's abilities. He crafted the perfect setting for soloists to improvise, as well as tightly orchestrated pieces that highlighted each musician's unique style. By doing this, he created a consistent tone for the orchestra and came up with unique sounds for each piece. Ellington's understanding of how each player sounded individually and how they fit together in a growing ensemble enabled him to write some of the most groundbreaking and brilliant jazz pieces ever.

The Grove Music dictionary mentions Creole Love Call as an example of Ellington using the human voice as a "jazz instrument" throughout his career. This showcases his early use of voice to add texture and color without words getting in the way. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington's ability to complement the styles of his soloists, a talent he continued to show throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece is full of interesting textures. Here's what it's got:
Chorus 1: A call-and-response between voice and reeds, where the voice starts smooth and melodic, then gets rougher at the end.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo that builds on the basic melody and emphasizes some extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, with a subtle syncopated piano phrase backing it up.
Chorus 4: The full band repeats the first chorus with a call-and-response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus, where the reeds start the call-and-response in a high register, backed by stop-time syncopation from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the first chorus structure, with call-and-response between voice and reeds. In this chorus, the voice takes on the "growl" technique, soloing like an instrument.
Tag: A short tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add tone color is just one of his many stylistic traits that are all over his work. In Hot and Bothered, he combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call-and-response phrase between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing creates a rich and complementary sound by blending the vocal elements of Miley's playing with the instrumental aspects of Cox's voice. It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing) takes this idea even further, as Ellington uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

There's this nagging feeling that she's had for a long time. It started when she was 14 and entered the teenage scene. It's been around for three years now, and she's convinced it's something more than just a thing - it's a person. But, weirdly, none of the guys she's met have caught her attention. Some have tried to impress her, but it's like they were speaking a different language. She's constantly questioning this strange desire, trying to figure out what's behind it. Her thoughts have come up with some theories, but nothing that really makes sense. So, she's just going with the flow, wondering what's going on with her.

At home, things are usually chill. Her parents are super laid-back and rarely argue with each other. They almost never argue with her either, except when she gets all independent and free-spirited. That's just her way of being, and they respect it. But today wasn't a chill day. As she wandered from room to room looking for some inspiration, she heard her mom let out a loud shriek from the kitchen. She rushed in, freaking out, and asked, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mom lying on the ground, gritting her teeth and saying "Ow" between short breaths. Her daughter sprang into action, trying to help. "Ouch ... sweetie, I ... need you to take me to the hospital." Her mom was in a lot of pain, so she quickly asked, "Okay, Mom, where can I pick you up?" Her mom gave her directions, and she was grateful she'd taken those self-defense classes - she was able to lift her mom and get her into the car.

The hospital had that weird mix of antiseptic and sickness smells, but she was too worried about her mom to notice. She rushed in and started calling for help, and soon a bunch of worried faces were around her mom, looking her over. They quickly wheeled her mom in, and she was left sitting there, worried sick. It turned out her mom had slipped off a step stool while trying to grab a vase from a high cabinet.

This research aimed to establish a link between following the "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) and reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke. To achieve this, a modified version of the Med diet, named "alternate Mediterranean" (aMed) diet, was used in the study. The aMed diet is characterized by a diet high in plant foods like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, but low in animal products and saturated fats. A moderate amount of alcohol was allowed. 

Past studies already showed that sticking to a Med diet is linked to lower risk of total and heart-related (CVD) mortality, and a trial proved that the Med diet is more effective than a low-fat diet in helping people lose weight and improve their cholesterol levels. However, previous research did not focus on the relationship between the Med diet and stroke.

This study tracked 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 who were part of the Nurses' Health Study, a long-term research project involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Over six occasions between 1984 and 2004, researchers calculated an aMed diet score based on the participants' self-reported diets, which they had detailed in food frequency questionnaires. More than 95% of the nurses remained involved in the study for the entire 20-year period. The accuracy of the reported diets was verified through separate studies. When medical records or death certificates weren't available, cases were considered "probable" and included in the research, which made up about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal heart attacks.

Essential data like body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and hormone use were also documented for each food frequency questionnaire. Starting in 1986, the participants' leisure-time physical activity was also recorded. To reduce individual variations and better represent long-term dietary habits, the researchers calculated the average aMed score over two years by combining scores from the previous two questionnaires. The study controlled for factors that could influence the results by adjusting for age, smoking, body mass index, menopausal status, hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Using a statistical model, the researchers analyzed the relationship between the aMed diet score and the risk of heart disease and stroke. The results showed that women who followed the Med diet closely, indicated by a higher aMed diet score, were at a lower risk of developing heart disease and stroke. Over the course of 20 years, the researchers found 2391 cases of CHD, 1763 cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths. Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk of developing both heart disease and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile, with a relative risk of 0.71.

Back in 2007, the United States was hit with a huge financial disaster. Unemployment skyrocketed, the housing market went down the drain, and many of America's biggest companies were left in shambles. This recession has stuck around, so we have to ask: what caused this mess, and how can we fix it? To get to the bottom of it, let's just say it all started with some super selfish and clueless politicians who made some pretty reckless decisions that tricked banks and companies into giving out bad loans. These loans went to people who couldn't afford them, and the financial system wasn't ready to handle it. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were forced to back these mortgages and package them up into some complicated securities. When people started defaulting on these loans, the banks were in a tight spot and passed the buck to the people who had bought the repackaged mortgages. It was like a big domino effect, and the whole economy got knocked down.

The roots of this mess go way back to the Clinton days, when President Clinton was trying to get re-elected. He wanted to be popular, so he relaxed the rules on lending, which set the stage for the sub-prime crisis years later. Steven Holmes from the New York Times wrote in 1999 that Fannie Mae was getting in big trouble because it was being forced to give out loans to people who couldn't afford them. Holmes even predicted that this would lead to a huge problem: "The government-backed company might tank in a recession, leading to a huge bailout like the one in the 1980s." And guess what? He was right! As we all know, bad lending can lead to a total economic meltdown.

A bunch of factors combined to make things worse, like these crazy new mortgage deals. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were all the rage back then, and they just made things more complicated. This led to people and companies getting way too invested in the housing market, making them super vulnerable to even small changes in prices. And then, BAM! The housing bubble burst, and all the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities got burned. The top five US investment banks were stuck with $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt, which was like 30% of the country's entire GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch got sold for pennies on the dollar, Lehman Brothers went down, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley had to become commercial banks with super strict rules. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in debt and got taken over by the government in 2008.

Okay, let's talk about exposition.  You know, that part in a story where you take a deep breath and try to wow your readers with your writing, but sometimes they just end up falling asleep or hitting the "Back" button in frustration.  Dr. Merlin has been there too, yelling at her monitor when she gets stuck in Too Much Information land.

Exposition is basically a writing nemesis that tempts you to tell instead of show.  You already know the basic rule, "Show, don't tell," but it's still easy to get sucked into boring passages that don't move the story forward.  Exposition is like that pesky voice in your head that says, "Just get the backstory out of the way so we can get to the exciting parts."

So, what is exposition exactly?  It's when you tell your readers what happened, usually in a straightforward way.  In movies, it's like when one character spouts off a bunch of info to another - like a "Rime of the Ancient Mariner" marathon.  As a writer, you're the one doing the telling.

Let's look at an example.  Imagine you're reading a story and suddenly you're hit with a few paragraphs of info about the heroine's love life: she met her husband, they got married in a big ceremony, and he got murdered right in front of her.  You wouldn't expect that whole sequence to take up two pages, with both characters only getting two lines of dialogue each.  You'd want the author to flesh out the husband's character through his words and actions, so you can see how much he loves his wife.  You'd also want to get a glimpse of how her life changed with him and how she felt about him.  That way, when the author tells you they had an amazing connection, you'll believe it and care about what happens to them.

In short, you want to add some meat to the bare bones of the story.  Instead of just saying "They met, they married, he died," you want to make it feel real.  It's tempting to rush through the details, but trust us, it's worth taking the time to make it count.  For example, let's say you're introducing a new character who used to be in the Air Force, works at a gas station, was married twice, and has all these other traits.  Don't give your readers a laundry list - show them through his actions and dialogue instead.  It's easier to get caught up in the story that way.

Today I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio - an NBC 4 live report this morning (August 13, 2011) and a few other stories. The first one I saw was about a dude named Shad Hostettler who knifed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. They showed his mugshot and, let's just say, he looked like the baddest of the bad. They only spent about two minutes on this story since it was still developing. I think they got it right, though. 
	The next story was about some 18-year-old named Travis Buyers getting shot in the Sharon Woods area. He was in critical condition, and the SWAT Team was on the case, but no arrests had been made yet. This story felt kinda short, and I'm wondering if it's because the victim was black. I've noticed that when minorities get hurt or get murdered, it's like they fade into the background. If a white kid or adult gets kidnapped or gets hurt, the news goes crazy, but when it's a minority person, they're lucky if they even get a mention. 
	They also did a piece on the gunshot hole in the Med-Flight helicopter. They said the bullet was probably from a .22 caliber rifle, and Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that'll lead to the shooter. 
	After that, they did a tease for some thunderstorms and rain on Saturday afternoon, saying the temps would be in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. They kept it short so we'd stay tuned. 
	They also had a story about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said the robber was a dark-skinned black guy wearing a hoodie and a sweatshirt. They went on and on about how dark he was, which seemed kinda weird. 
	Another story was about some dude named Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin who'd been caught selling a lot of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. What caught my eye was when they said he got sentenced to 300 months in prison instead of 25 years. I'm not sure what the point was there - maybe they thought it sounded harsher or what. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, but that didn't seem super relevant to the story.

There's a special connection between brothers that's unbreakable and unshakeable - a bond that's filled with a mix of emotions like love, pride, jealousy, and sometimes even cruelty. Brothers have a way of understanding each other that's deeper than any other kind of connection, and when they look at their brother, they see a reflection of themselves. It's when things get really tough that the true nature of this bond really comes out - whether it's good or bad. When these emotions are clear, they come with a big price tag. Part of understanding the emotions that come with being a brother is dealing with the consequences that come with them. When you can look a brother in the eye and see your own reflection staring back at you, you see yourself for who you really are, not how others see you. It's in your actions and the consequences of those actions that you really find out what you're made of. In the story "The Scarlet Ibis", two brothers explore this theme and all the crazy emotions that come with it. They set out on this wild journey through a vivid and beautiful landscape, but it's all for nothing in the end. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the most intense moment, and only one brother makes it out alive. The theme is shown through how the characters act and talk to each other, and also through the narrator's point of view, which helps us see how the protagonist feels and sees the world around him. 

The whole story is all about one main emotion: the protagonist's pride. From the very beginning, he's super resentful of his little brother, Doodle, who was born with a weak heart and can't do all the cool things the protagonist wants to teach him. He wanted a brother who could be his partner in adventure, but Doodle's condition makes that impossible. The protagonist even thought about killing Doodle at one point, which is just crazy, but when Doodle smiles at him, it makes him realize he actually loves his little brother deep down. It's like his heart was beating with love all along, even if he didn't want to admit it. The story shows how the protagonist's love and anger towards Doodle are always at war, and in the end, it's a battle he can't win.

My brain is like, super complicated and creative, you know? It's like it's got its own way of processing information. Over time, how we've described it has changed with the advancements in tech. Initially, it was like a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and now it's compared to a computer. However, keep in mind that these comparisons aren't that accurate and might lead to some pretty big misunderstandings. 

When I'm learning about my brain, I'm picking up that it gets info from my senses first. It takes the physical things like touch, heat, sound waves, or light and turns them into these electrochemical signals. The brain breaks down this info in two ways – bottom-up and top-down processing. When I look at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together simple stuff like color, orientation, and where the box starts and ends. Then top-down processing kicks in and uses that info to help me figure out what the box is, like a box and not a hole in the background. 

After that, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which brain processes I should let it in. For instance, when I look down at my shoes, my brain processes every blade of grass, but the attention filter keeps me from actually seeing them. But if I'm trying to hear my name in a crowded room, that filter lets the sound through. There are lots of stages of processing, and my brain goes back and forth with the attention filter a bunch of times.

In order for my brain to process info, it's gotta store it first. There are different types of memory – sensory, working, and long-term. First, it's gotta be encoded, and there are different ways to do that depending on the type of sensory info. For example, if someone's talking, my brain can encode it based on what it looks like, what it sounds like, or what it means. Once it's stored, my brain's gotta keep it. Animal studies have shown that working memory, which is like, temporary, is kept by an electrical signal looping through some neurons. Long-term memory is thought to be stored in the structure of certain proteins.

There are lots of different models explaining how the brain organizes knowledge, and they're all based on different things – like how people remember stuff or how computers work or how the brain is wired. One of these models is the semantic network, which says that there are these nodes representing concepts, and they're connected based on how related they are. For example, in a semantic network, "chair" might be connected to "table," which is connected to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley's novel Brave New World paints a picture of a dystopian future where technology and a capitalistic society reinforce each other. In this world, people value community over individuality and are conditioned from birth to seek instant gratification above all else. The citizens are essentially pawns in a larger game, trapped in a single ideology controlled by the World Controller. By examining the novel through a Marxist lens, it becomes clear that Huxley has some major issues with these emerging systems. Terms like homogeny and reification are scattered throughout the book, hinting at his concerns about the economy of his time. 

Huxley uses satire to poke fun at capitalism by highlighting the concept of false consciousness. This basically means that regular folks don't really know their place in the economic hierarchy; they're too busy looking out for themselves. This is essentially the result of ideological control over the working class, something that's super obvious in Brave New World. The lower classes are basically mindless drones, conditioned through hypnopædia to desire, consume, and indulge above all else. The World Controller is behind it all, manipulating the masses like pawns on a chessboard. The idea of hegemony – where one group dominates another – is totally at play here. The lower classes are oblivious to the manipulation, blindly following the ideology that keeps them in line. The upper classes, on the other hand, are aware of it, but they just accept their place in society. Only a few characters, like Bernard, seem to care about the bigger picture. The way the social classes interact with each other is a huge indication of the oppressive nature of capitalism.

In Brave New World, relationships between people are basically non-existent. The novel seems to strip away any depth or emotion from its characters, even the main ones. Huxley might be suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together is stripping people of their free will and individuality. Love and intense emotions are nonexistent, replaced by shallow interactions that are purely physical or superficial. The way characters talk about each other, focusing on appearance rather than substance, is a big clue. The fact that each social class is content with their place in the hierarchy is a clear indication of how capitalism affects people's perceptions of themselves and their place in society.

So, I've been at University Park for two and a half years. It's basically four and a half semesters for those who are counting. Getting around campus can be a real pain in the butt. Last year, I was stuck in an East Halls dorm room, which is basically the last stop on campus, except for the stadium and the Bryce Jordan Center. I'd have to trudge from my place in Stuart Hall all the way to the Willard building near the middle of campus, which would take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially if the weather's lousy. I talked to an old alum who's not much older than me, and they told me that not too long ago, the East Halls dorms were cut off from the rest of school by a huge empty space. Nowadays, that space is filled with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As the campus keeps expanding, it's getting harder to get from one place to another. So, what's the solution to this problem? For a college campus, it's gotta be bikes. But it's not just about having a bike; people need to ride them, and the campus needs to be bike-friendly.

I was chatting with a friend who recently got back into biking after taking a few years off, and he was saying how he wondered why he ever stopped. "Bikes are awesome," he said, "for a few years, it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it's the only way to get around." Not only is biking good for you, but it's also super efficient. You can pack a bowl of oatmeal and get 30 miles or more out of it – not bad for a little exercise. I live off campus, just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest thing I did this year was buy a bike. Now, every day, I have class in Thomas building, which is a 25-minute walk from my place. But with a bike, I can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal hard enough. The problem is, Pollock Road is the most direct route to Thomas building from my house, but it's not the easiest road to navigate, bike or not. I've got to give credit to walking, but personally, I'm too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable option, and it would take up a ton of my time – over two and a half hours every week. That's time I just can't afford to waste.
